   "source": [
    "# FeatureEstimationDemo\n",
    "\n",
    "### Read example BIDS data \n",
    "\n",
    "In this demo the basic offline workflow of py_neuromodulation will be demonstrated. For that, the example BIDS dataset in *pyneuromodulation/examples/data/* will be analyzed. \n",
    "The parametrization `nm_settings.json` is stored in the package directory *pyneuromodulation/nm_settings.json*, a `nm_channels.csv` is created given the *channel_type* information from the BIDS data. \n",
    "\n",
    "A projection will be defined based on the *pyneuromodulation/grid_cortex.tsv* and *pyneuromodulation/grid_subcortex.tsv* files. Band power features and sharpwave features will then be estimated and projected to the provided grid. \n",
    "\n",
    "First, necessary modules will be included and the BIDS_PATH and RUN_PATH, the path to the BIDS brainvision run file, will be defined given the example."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "a1959766",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

    "PATH_OUT = os.path.join(\n",
    "    PATH_BIDS,\n",
    "    'derivatives'\n",
    ")"

   "id": "5c3273dc",

   "source": [

    "Importantly *ANALOG_ROT_R_1* is used as a target channel. After feature estimation, this channel will be normalized and added in a time aligned manner to the features output csv file. \n",
    "\n",
    "Next we will check the used settings:"

       " 're_referencing': True,\n",

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b80afb94",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As defined, data will be **resampled**, **normalized** and **rereferenced** (as defined in the nm_channels) before feature estimation. Then, **bandpower features**, **sharpwave features** and **hjorth parameters** are calculated. Additionally, gamma band features will be Kalman filtered. Since *project_cortex* is set to true, projection to a grid is also enabled. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Grid projection\n",
    "\n",
    "Next we will read the cortical grid, defined in *pyneuromodulation/grid_cortex.tsv*, and calculate the **projection matrix** from individual channels to the grid:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0365da48",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can now inspect the individual coordinates, and the projected grid points. Therfore we read first a standard MNI hull, defined in the plot folder:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e4281c5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since the grid is defined for the left hemisphere, we might switch the x coordinates for right electrodes. Then the ECoG channel coordinates and used grid points are visualized:  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "69e92490",
   "metadata": {},

     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "No Error occurred when testing the settings.\n",
      "No data specified. Sanity checks related to the length of the signal relative to the filter order will be skipped.\n",
      "Setting up band-stop filter\n",
      "\n",
      "FIR filter parameters\n",
      "---------------------\n",
      "Designing a one-pass, zero-phase, non-causal bandstop filter:\n",
      "- Windowed time-domain design (firwin) method\n",
      "- Hamming window with 0.0194 passband ripple and 53 dB stopband attenuation\n",
      "- Lower transition bandwidth: 7.50 Hz\n",
      "- Upper transition bandwidth: 7.50 Hz\n",
      "- Filter length: 999 samples (0.999 sec)\n",
      "\n"
     ]
    }

   "source": [
    "As visible, only grid points are active (channel data is projected unto them as shown in yellow) within the *max_dist* of every individual channel for the cortical and subcortical grid (as specified in the `nm_settings.json`). \n",
    "\n",
    "Next, the **rereference** and **resample** classes get instantiated, and an acquisition system is simulated by a **generator**:"
   ]

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Feature Estimation \n",
    "\n",
    "Now the used **feature** and **run_analysis** classes are instantiated. Here FIR Filters and Kalman Filters are parametrized. During online feature estimation filters only have to be applied, instead of a repetitive calculatation, which saves computational time. "

   "id": "ae4e559f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   "id": "a728b41d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Sharpwave features\n",
    "Now let's investigate sharpwave features. First, data for a specific channel is bandpass filtered in a predefined range (here 5 - 80 Hz)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "199cf49f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "normalize_samples = int(pn_stream.settings[\"raw_normalization_settings\"][\"normalization_time\"] * pn_stream.fs)\n",
    "raw_norm = nm_normalization.normalize_raw(\n",
    "    ieeg_batch,\n",
    "    None,\n",
    "    normalize_samples,\n",
    "    pn_stream.fs,\n",
    "    method='mean',\n",
    "    clip=False\n",
    ")[0]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ed605f4b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then troughs and peaks are identified, subsequently different features are estimated. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "89d21c77",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this example plot, the trough sharpness is visualized for the estimated data batch:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "11e94d16",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# data is being filtered in get_sharpwave_features\n",
    "ch_idx = 10\n",
    "data = raw_norm[ch_idx,:]\n",
    "pn_stream.features.sw_features.initialize_sw_features() \n",
    "\n",
    "pn_stream.features.sw_features.filtered_data = np.convolve(\n",
    "    data,\n",
    "    pn_stream.features.sw_features.filter,\n",
    "    mode='same'\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "pn_stream.features.sw_features.analyze_waveform()\n",
